Research consistently shows:

# Inferential Thinking

depends on:

```text id="m7i2qe"
background knowledge
and
text evidence
```

Inference is NOT:

```text id="r2i8qe"
guessing
without
support
```

Students learn:

```text id="x5i4qe"
read closely
→ gather clues
→ connect evidence
→ infer meaning
→ justify thinking
```

This develops:

* close reading
* analytical thinking
* reasoning
* evidence use
* deeper comprehension

This becomes:

# Evidence-Based Thinking

Common misconceptions:

students may believe:

```text id="p8i1qe"
inference
=
personal opinion
```

or:

```text id="u3i6qe"
answers
must be
stated directly
```

Some may:

```text id="c5i9qe"
ignore
text clues
```

without understanding:

```text id="k2i4qe"
inferences
combine
evidence
and reasoning
```

Students may also think:

```text id="n6i3qe"
one detail
proves
everything
```

instead of recognizing:

```text id="t1i7qe"
strong
inferences
use
multiple clues
```

Example:

text says:

```text id="q7i2qe"
Sam grabbed
an umbrella
and hurried
outside
```

students may answer:

```text id="v4i8qe"
Sam likes
umbrellas
```

instead of inferring:

```text id="a5i3qe"
it may
be raining
```

because:

```text id="g3i7rx"
evidence
supports
inference
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="v9i1rt"
reasoned interpretation
```

For Grade 6:

focus includes:

Text Evidence:

* quotation
* details
* citation
* proof
* support

Inference:

* implied meaning
* character motives
* cause and effect
* prediction
* synthesis

